 The compilers of the Summa Halensis first articulated many positions that eventually become closely associated with the Franciscan tradition on issues like the nature of God, the proof for God's existence, free will, the transcendentals, and Christology. This book is essential reading for anyone wishing to understand the ways in which medieval thinkers employed philosophical concepts in a theological context as well as the evolution of Franciscan thought and its legacy to modernity.A Reader in Early Franciscan Theology is available from the publisher on an open-access basis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aTheology, DoctrinalvEarly works to 1800. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh  aAlexander of Hales.  aChristology.  aFranciscan.  aJohn of La Rochelle.  aTrinity.  adivine infinity.  afree will.  amedieval philosophy.  amedieval theology.  amoral law.  aontological argument.  atranscendentals.1 aBychkov, Oleg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchumacher, Lydia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075166640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823298860zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823298860zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823298860/original  a978-3-11-075166-6 Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA